NFL Passer Rating Analysis¶

By Clay Miller¶

Introduction¶

A big part of a team's ability to succeed in the National Football League is how good of a quarterback the team has. Many say that quarterback is the most important position, and although a team can succeed without a good quarterback, it is by far the biggest determination of a team's success. There are many metrics used to measure quarterback statistics, but passer rating is the most commonly used one. Passer rating is calculated in the NFL by using a player's passing attempts, completions, yards, touchdowns, and interceptions on a scale from 0 to 158.3.

This is a link to the Wikipedia page on passer rating: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passer_rating#:~:text=Passer%20rating%20

Within this project, I will analyze the success of teams in terms of their Win-Loss percentage as an effect of the team's passer rating, displaying the importance of the quarterback position on the success of a team from the year 2003-2020.

Getting Data¶

The links to the website the data is pulled from for each year is below, stored in a variable titled "url20XX" for the year the data is for. For a portion of the years a tie did not take place and therefore the website dropped the tie column for that year instead of having an entire row of zeroes for the tie column, so I separated the URLs into ties and no ties.

Below is a function used for each year between 2003 and 2020, with a parameter for the link to the year, whether a tie took place that year, and the year. I then used the requests package to get the URL and the beautiful soup package to give the html of the site. I used the find function to get the table for the AFC and then put all of the table information into an array named data. If the year had a tie column I then put it into a dataframe for the AFC otherwise I put every column present and a tie column full of zeroes into a dataframe. I then dropped the rows and columns that were not used and re-indexed after dropping them. I repeated the process for the table for the NFC, putting it into a dataframe for the NFC at the end in the same fashion.

I then created a dataframe that combined the two leagues and converted the win loss percentage to a float for later calculations. I also sorted by that column and re-indexed based on it, and created a year column that the parameter is used for, finally re-ordering the columns. The last step was to use the comment package in order to get the data for the last table, which is the one containing the passer rating data. I put it into a dataframe and dropped every column except the team and rate so that I could then merge the dataframe with the records with this one to have the rates as well. I finally sorted by rate and returned that year's dataframe.

In [3]:
def getyeardata(u, m, y):
    response = requests.get(u)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, "html.parser")
    soup.prettify()
    htmltable = soup.find(id="AFC")
    data = []
    tablebody = htmltable.find('tbody')
    rows = tablebody.find_all('tr')
    for singlerow in rows:
        names = singlerow.find_all('a')
        names = [element.text.strip() for element in names]
        cols = singlerow.find_all('td')
        cols = [element.text.strip() for element in cols]
        cols.append([element for element in names])
        data.append([element for element in cols])
    if m == 1:
        afcdata = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['W', 'L', 'T', 'W-L%', 'PF', 'PA', 'PD', 'MoV', 'SoS', 'SRS', 'OSRS', 'DSRS', 'Team'])
    else:
        afcdata = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['W', 'L', 'W-L%', 'PF', 'PA', 'PD', 'MoV', 'SoS', 'SRS', 'OSRS', 'DSRS', 'Team'])
        afcdata = afcdata.assign(T='0')
    afcdata = afcdata.drop([0, 5, 10, 15])
    afcdata = afcdata.drop(columns=['PF', 'PA', 'PD', 'MoV', 'SoS', 'SRS', 'OSRS', 'DSRS'])
    afcdata.index = range(16)
    htmltable = soup.find(id="NFC")
    data = []
    tablebody = htmltable.find('tbody')
    rows = tablebody.find_all('tr')
    for singlerow in rows:
        names = singlerow.find_all('a')
        names = [element.text.strip() for element in names]
        cols = singlerow.find_all('td')
        cols = [element.text.strip() for element in cols]
        cols.append([element for element in names])
        data.append([element for element in cols])
    if m == 1:
        nfcdata = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['W', 'L', 'T', 'W-L%', 'PF', 'PA', 'PD', 'MoV', 'SoS', 'SRS', 'OSRS', 'DSRS', 'Team'])
    else:
        nfcdata = pd.DataFrame(data, columns=['W', 'L', 'W-L%', 'PF', 'PA', 'PD', 'MoV', 'SoS', 'SRS', 'OSRS', 'DSRS', 'Team'])
        nfcdata = nfcdata.assign(T='0')
    nfcdata = nfcdata.drop([0, 5, 10, 15])
    nfcdata = nfcdata.drop(columns=['PF', 'PA', 'PD', 'MoV', 'SoS', 'SRS', 'OSRS', 'DSRS'])
    nfcdata.index = range(16, 32)
    frames = [afcdata, nfcdata]
    result = pd.concat(frames)
    result['W-L%'] = result['W-L%'].astype('float64') 
    result = result.sort_values(by=['W-L%'], ascending=True)
    result.index = range(32)
    result['Year'] = y
    result['Team'] = list(map(lambda x: x[0], result.Team))
    result = result[['Team', 'Year', 'W', 'L', 'T', 'W-L%']]
    comments = soup.find_all(string=lambda text: isinstance(text, Comment))
    tables = []
    for each in comments:
        if 'table' in each:
            try:
                tables.append(pd.read_html(each)[0])
            except:
                continue
    pasdata = pd.DataFrame(tables[4], columns=['Rk', 'Tm', 'G', 'Cmp', 'Att', 'Cmp%', 'Yds', 'TD', 'TD%', 'Int', 'Int%', 'Lng', 'Y/A' 'AY/A', 'Y/C', 'Y/G', 'Rate', 'Sk', 'Yds', 'Sk%', 'NY/A', 'ANY/A', '4QC', 'GWD', 'EXP'])
    pasdata['Team'] = pasdata['Tm']
    pasdata = pasdata.drop([32, 33, 34])
    pasdata = pasdata.drop(columns=['Tm', 'Rk', 'G', 'Cmp', 'Att', 'Cmp%', 'Yds', 'TD', 'TD%', 'Int', 'Int%', 'Lng', 'Y/A' 'AY/A', 'Y/C', 'Y/G', 'Sk', 'Yds', 'Sk%', 'NY/A', 'ANY/A', '4QC', 'GWD', 'EXP'])
    pasdata = pasdata[['Team', 'Rate']]
    result = pd.merge(result, pasdata, on='Team')
    result = result.sort_values(by=['Rate'], ascending=True)
    return result

I then created a dataframe for each year by calling the function with each year's URL as well as a 1 for if there was a tie and a 0 otherwise and the final parameter being the year for the year column. I then combined them into one dataframe containing the data from 2003-2020. I then put the data into sql in order to make sure I have a copy of the data and lastly I changed the names of the teams that relocated in order to keep the data consistent to what team it is and not what city the team is in. I then outputted the beginning of the dataframe.

conn = sqlite3.connect('data.sqlite')
df.to_sql('prdata', conn, if_exists='replace', index=False)
df = pd.read_sql('select * from prdata', conn)
df["Team"] = df["Team"].apply(lambda x: x.replace("Los Angeles Rams", "St. Louis Rams"))
df["Team"] = df["Team"].apply(lambda x: x.replace("Los Angeles Chargers", "San Diego Chargers"))
df["Team"] = df["Team"].apply(lambda x: x.replace("Washington Football Team", "Washington Redskins"))
df["Team"] = df["Team"].apply(lambda x: x.replace("Las Vegas Raiders", "Oakland Raiders"))

For the AFC north, it is clear that each team has a positive linear relationship between passer rate and win loss percentage, and only Pittsburgh has many points that are spread from the regression line. For the AFC East, the Jets actually have way less of a positive relationship then any other AFC team, while Buffalo has a very sharp increase over time compared to the rest of the division. For the West, Kansas City is similar to Buffalo, and finally for the South Houston is similar to the Jets in not having a very positive relationship. Tennessee is also sort of in this group, and the common trend is teams that stay around the same record over time with average quarterback play for the most part is an explanation for the teams with less of a positive slope. Kansas City and Buffalo I feel can be explained by how they both now have quarterbacks that are performing amazing while both franchises have had really low points over the 15 year span.

For the NFC North, Chicago has a flat line of a slope showing no positive relationship between passer rating and win loss percentage while Green Bay has a very steep slope. For the NFC East, New York also has a flat line showing almost no relationship between passer rating and win percentage. For the West, St. Louis also has a steep increase and for the South Tampa Bay does. Green Bay, St. Louis and Tampa Bay do all have very good quarterback play at the moment while they did not have good quarterback play at a point in the 15 year span so that explains those. The curious ones are the Bears and Giants, considering the 2 teams combined for 3 super bowl appearances in the span despite average quarterback play not contributing to their success. The answer I would suggest is both teams relied on their defense for those years more than their quarterback, which is definitely an outlier in today's NFL.

Machine Learning¶

Next, I used robust scaler and label encoder in the preprocessing package of sklearn to turn the categorical data into numbers starting at 0, and to remove the median and scale the data according to the IQR for the passer rate and win-loss percentage. I also dropped the columns not necessary for machine learning and set X to be the dataframe with just Team, Year and Rate standardized while y is just the win-loss percentage of every row in an array.

In [11]:
X = df
rc = RobustScaler()
numerical = ['W-L%', 'Rate']
X[numerical] = rc.fit_transform(X[numerical])
y = df['W-L%']
X = X.drop(columns=['W', 'L', 'T', 'W-L%'])
le = sklearn.preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
X['Team'] = le.fit_transform(X['Team'])
X['Year'] = le.fit_transform(X['Year'])

Splitting the data¶

I split the data into a training set and a testing set in order to train the method on the training set and test it on the testing set to see the accuracy.

In [12]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 12)
X_train.shape, y_train.shape, X_test.shape, y_test.shape

Linear Regression¶

Linear regression, or ordinary least squares (OLS) finds the parameters w and b that minimize the mean squared error between predictions and the true regression targets, y, on the training set.

In [13]:
# instantiate the model
lr = LinearRegression()
# fit the model 
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

#predicting the target value from the model for the samples
y_test_lr = lr.predict(X_test)
y_train_lr = lr.predict(X_train)

#computing the accuracy of the model performance
acc_train_lr = lr.score(X_train, y_train)
acc_test_lr = lr.score(X_test, y_test)

#computing root mean squared error (RMSE)
rmse_train_lr = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_lr))
rmse_test_lr = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_lr))

print("Linear Regression: Accuracy on training Data: {:.3f}".format(acc_train_lr))
print("Linear Regression: Accuracy on test Data: {:.3f}".format(acc_test_lr))
print('\nLinear Regression: The RMSE of the training set is:', rmse_train_lr)
print('Linear Regression: The RMSE of the testing set is:', rmse_test_lr)

SVM Regression¶

The objective of SVR is to consider the points that are within the decision boundary line. The best fit line is the hyperplane that has a maximum number of points.

In [15]:
sc_X = StandardScaler()
sc_y = StandardScaler()
X = sc_X.fit_transform(X)
y = sc_y.fit_transform(pd.DataFrame(y))
# instantiate the model 
clf = SVR(kernel = 'rbf')
# fit the model 
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

#predicting the target value from the model for the samples
y_test_clf = clf.predict(X_test)
y_train_clf = clf.predict(X_train)

#computing the accuracy of the model performance
acc_train_clf = clf.score(X_train, y_train)
acc_test_clf = clf.score(X_test, y_test)

#computing root mean squared error (RMSE)
rmse_train_clf = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_clf))
rmse_test_clf = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_clf))

print("SVM Regression: Accuracy on training Data: {:.3f}".format(acc_train_clf))
print("SVM Regression: Accuracy on test Data: {:.3f}".format(acc_test_clf))
print('\nSVM Regression: The RMSE of the training set is:', rmse_train_clf)
print('SVM Regression: The RMSE of the testing set is:', rmse_test_clf)
